<!--
  wazuh-home (manager): rules for Vault VM DNS visibility, FTL-DB pipeline.

  Append inside /var/ossec/etc/rules/local_rules.xml on the manager.
  After editing, validate + restart:
      sudo /var/ossec/bin/wazuh-analysisd -t
      sudo systemctl restart wazuh-manager

  Goal: surface every Vault VM DNS query as a Wazuh alert with full
  metadata (qtype, query, status label, blocked-or-not boolean) in a
  single event. The data source is the structured JSON log emitted by
  the sidecar at sidecar/pihole-ftl-tail.py, tailed by the Wazuh agent
  on the Pi-hole VM via pihole-agent.localfile.xml.

  Three-rule chain:
    - 100250 (level 0): catch-all "any vault_dns event from the
      sidecar". Archived only if logall_json is on; never alerts.
      All other rules in this chain depend on it via if_sid so we
      don't have to repeat the discriminator field check.
    - 100251 (level 3): the query was actually resolved (forwarded
      / cached / etc, blocked=false). Visible in alerts.json + the
      dashboard, but lower-priority than blocked queries.
    - 100252 (level 6): the query was blocked (blocked=true), by
      ANY mechanism (gravity adlist, manual exact-deny, regex,
      upstream-NULL, externally-blocked NXDOMAIN, etc). The
      sidecar normalizes all block flavors into the boolean.

  Why this replaces the old chain (100190 / 100195 / 100200 / 100210):

  The previous approach decoded Pi-hole's dnsmasq text log in two
  separate decoders, fired four rules, and used a Wazuh correlation
  rule to tie a "blocked" event back to a Vault VM "query" event by
  same_field=query within a timeframe. That worked for some block
  flavors but missed others (Pi-hole emits four-plus different
  syntactic patterns for different block sources, and we kept finding
  new ones). The FTL-DB sidecar reads Pi-hole's normalized status
  column and emits one merged event per query, so the manager-side
  chain collapses to a single decoder (Wazuh's built-in JSON one) plus
  these three rules. No correlation needed; the sidecar already merged
  the data before Wazuh saw it.

  Why no <decoded_as>json</decoded_as> bind in 100250's parents:
  Wazuh's built-in JSON decoder fires on any line that parses as JSON
  on a localfile with log_format=json. We don't add a custom decoder
  here. The discriminator that scopes alerts to "events from the
  sidecar specifically" is the event_type field embedded in every JSON
  line by the sidecar.

  Replace 192.168.50.3 below with the actual Vault VM IP if it's
  different in your environment. (The sidecar already filters at SQL
  level to that IP before emitting events, so this rule's <srcip>
  check is belt-and-braces; it ALSO catches misconfiguration where
  the sidecar's CLIENT_FILTER got changed but the rule wasn't.)
-->
<group name="dns,pihole,vaultwarden">

  <!-- Base: every event the sidecar emits, scoped via event_type.
       Level 0 = archived (with logall_json) but no alert. -->
  <rule id="100250" level="0">
    <decoded_as>json</decoded_as>
    <field name="event_type">vault_dns</field>
    <description>Vault VM DNS event: $(query) [$(status)]</description>
  </rule>

  <!-- Resolved query: the Vault VM got a real DNS answer.
       blocked=false in the JSON. Level 3 alert in dashboard. -->
  <rule id="100251" level="3">
    <if_sid>100250</if_sid>
    <srcip>192.168.50.3</srcip>
    <field name="blocked">false</field>
    <description>Vault VM DNS resolved: $(query) [$(status)]</description>
  </rule>

  <!-- Blocked query: the Vault VM's query did NOT resolve to a real
       answer, regardless of which Pi-hole mechanism blocked it.
       blocked=true in the JSON. Level 6 alert: higher priority than
       resolutions but not active-response territory. -->
  <rule id="100252" level="6">
    <if_sid>100250</if_sid>
    <srcip>192.168.50.3</srcip>
    <field name="blocked">true</field>
    <description>Vault VM DNS BLOCKED: $(query) [$(status)]</description>
  </rule>

</group>
